==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Polite
<hw>Po*lite"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Politer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Politest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>politus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>polire</ets> to polish: cf. F.
<ets>poli</ets>. See <er>Polish</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Smooth; polished.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rays of light falling on a <qex>polite</qex> surface.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Smooth and refined in behavior or manners; well
bred; courteous; complaisant; obliging; civil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He marries, bows at court, and grows <qex>polite</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characterized by refinement, or a high degree of
finish; <as>as, <ex>polite</ex> literature</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Polished; refined; well bred; courteous; affable;
urbane; civil; courtly; elegant; genteel.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Polite
<hw>Po*lite"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To polish; to refine; to render
polite.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Ray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Politely</ent>⟦br⟧
